#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:5
msgid "Parametrizing tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:9
msgid ""
"``pytest`` allows to easily parametrize test functions. For basic docs, see :"
"ref:`parametrize-basics`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:12
msgid "In the following we provide some examples using the builtin mechanisms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:16
msgid "Generating parameters combinations, depending on command line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:20
msgid ""
"Let's say we want to execute a test with different computation parameters "
"and the parameter range shall be determined by a command line argument.  "
"Let's first write a simple (do-nothing) computation test::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:24
msgid ""
"# content of test_compute.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_compute(param1):\n"
"    assert param1 < 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:29
msgid "Now we add a test configuration like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:31
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_addoption(parser):\n"
"    parser.addoption(\"--all\", action=\"store_true\",\n"
"        help=\"run all combinations\")\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    if 'param1' in metafunc.fixturenames:\n"
"        if metafunc.config.option.all:\n"
"            end = 5\n"
"        else:\n"
"            end = 2\n"
"        metafunc.parametrize(\"param1\", range(end))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:45
msgid "This means that we only run 2 tests if we do not pass ``--all``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:47
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_compute.py\n"
"..\n"
"2 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:51
msgid ""
"We run only two computations, so we see two dots. let's run the full monty::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:54
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q --all\n"
"....F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_compute[4] ________\n"
"\n"
"param1 = 4\n"
"\n"
"    def test_compute(param1):\n"
">       assert param1 < 4\n"
"E       assert 4 < 4\n"
"\n"
"test_compute.py:3: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed, 4 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:68
msgid ""
"As expected when running the full range of ``param1`` values we'll get an "
"error on the last one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:73
msgid "Different options for test IDs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:75
msgid ""
"pytest will build a string that is the test ID for each set of values in a "
"parametrized test. These IDs can be used with ``-k`` to select specific "
"cases to run, and they will also identify the specific case when one is "
"failing. Running pytest with ``--collect-only`` will show the generated IDs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:80
msgid ""
"Numbers, strings, booleans and None will have their usual string "
"representation used in the test ID. For other objects, pytest will make a "
"string based on the argument name::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:84
msgid ""
"# content of test_time.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"from datetime import datetime, timedelta\n"
"\n"
"testdata = [\n"
"    (datetime(2001, 12, 12), datetime(2001, 12, 11), timedelta(1)),\n"
"    (datetime(2001, 12, 11), datetime(2001, 12, 12), timedelta(-1)),\n"
"]\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"a,b,expected\", testdata)\n"
"def test_timedistance_v0(a, b, expected):\n"
"    diff = a - b\n"
"    assert diff == expected\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"a,b,expected\", testdata, ids=[\"forward\", "
"\"backward\"])\n"
"def test_timedistance_v1(a, b, expected):\n"
"    diff = a - b\n"
"    assert diff == expected\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def idfn(val):\n"
"    if isinstance(val, (datetime,)):\n"
"        # note this wouldn't show any hours/minutes/seconds\n"
"        return val.strftime('%Y%m%d')\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"a,b,expected\", testdata, ids=idfn)\n"
"def test_timedistance_v2(a, b, expected):\n"
"    diff = a - b\n"
"    assert diff == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:120
msgid "In ``test_timedistance_v0``, we let pytest generate the test IDs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:122
msgid ""
"In ``test_timedistance_v1``, we specified ``ids`` as a list of strings which "
"were used as the test IDs. These are succinct, but can be a pain to maintain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:125
msgid ""
"In ``test_timedistance_v2``, we specified ``ids`` as a function that can "
"generate a string representation to make part of the test ID. So our "
"``datetime`` values use the label generated by ``idfn``, but because we "
"didn't generate a label for ``timedelta`` objects, they are still using the "
"default pytest representation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:131
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_time.py --collect-only\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"<Module 'test_time.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v0[a0-b0-expected0]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v0[a1-b1-expected1]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v1[forward]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v1[backward]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v2[20011212-20011211-expected0]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_timedistance_v2[20011211-20011212-expected1]'>\n"
"\n"
"======= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:147
msgid "A quick port of \"testscenarios\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:151
msgid ""
"Here is a quick port to run tests configured with `test scenarios`_, an add-"
"on from Robert Collins for the standard unittest framework. We only have to "
"work a bit to construct the correct arguments for pytest's :py:func:"
"`Metafunc.parametrize`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:156
msgid ""
"# content of test_scenarios.py\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    idlist = []\n"
"    argvalues = []\n"
"    for scenario in metafunc.cls.scenarios:\n"
"        idlist.append(scenario[0])\n"
"        items = scenario[1].items()\n"
"        argnames = [x[0] for x in items]\n"
"        argvalues.append(([x[1] for x in items]))\n"
"    metafunc.parametrize(argnames, argvalues, ids=idlist, scope=\"class\")\n"
"\n"
"scenario1 = ('basic', {'attribute': 'value'})\n"
"scenario2 = ('advanced', {'attribute': 'value2'})\n"
"\n"
"class TestSampleWithScenarios:\n"
"    scenarios = [scenario1, scenario2]\n"
"\n"
"    def test_demo1(self, attribute):\n"
"        assert isinstance(attribute, str)\n"
"\n"
"    def test_demo2(self, attribute):\n"
"        assert isinstance(attribute, str)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:180
msgid "this is a fully self-contained example which you can run with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:182
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_scenarios.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_scenarios.py ....\n"
"\n"
"======= 4 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:192
msgid ""
"If you just collect tests you'll also nicely see 'advanced' and 'basic' as "
"variants for the test function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:195
msgid ""
"$ py.test --collect-only test_scenarios.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"<Module 'test_scenarios.py'>\n"
"  <Class 'TestSampleWithScenarios'>\n"
"    <Instance '()'>\n"
"      <Function 'test_demo1[basic]'>\n"
"      <Function 'test_demo2[basic]'>\n"
"      <Function 'test_demo1[advanced]'>\n"
"      <Function 'test_demo2[advanced]'>\n"
"\n"
"======= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:210
msgid ""
"Note that we told ``metafunc.parametrize()`` that your scenario values "
"should be considered class-scoped.  With pytest-2.3 this leads to a resource-"
"based ordering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:215
msgid "Deferring the setup of parametrized resources"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:219
msgid ""
"The parametrization of test functions happens at collection time.  It is a "
"good idea to setup expensive resources like DB connections or subprocess "
"only when the actual test is run. Here is a simple example how you can "
"achieve that, first the actual test requiring a ``db`` object::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:225
msgid ""
"# content of test_backends.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"def test_db_initialized(db):\n"
"    # a dummy test\n"
"    if db.__class__.__name__ == \"DB2\":\n"
"        pytest.fail(\"deliberately failing for demo purposes\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:233
msgid ""
"We can now add a test configuration that generates two invocations of the "
"``test_db_initialized`` function and also implements a factory that creates "
"a database object for the actual test invocations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:237
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    if 'db' in metafunc.fixturenames:\n"
"        metafunc.parametrize(\"db\", ['d1', 'd2'], indirect=True)\n"
"\n"
"class DB1:\n"
"    \"one database object\"\n"
"class DB2:\n"
"    \"alternative database object\"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def db(request):\n"
"    if request.param == \"d1\":\n"
"        return DB1()\n"
"    elif request.param == \"d2\":\n"
"        return DB2()\n"
"    else:\n"
"        raise ValueError(\"invalid internal test config\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:258
msgid "Let's first see how it looks like at collection time::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:260
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_backends.py --collect-only\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"<Module 'test_backends.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_db_initialized[d1]'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_db_initialized[d2]'>\n"
"\n"
"======= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:271
msgid "And then when we run the test::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:273
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_backends.py\n"
".F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_db_initialized[d2] ________\n"
"\n"
"db = <conftest.DB2 object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_db_initialized(db):\n"
"        # a dummy test\n"
"        if db.__class__.__name__ == \"DB2\":\n"
">           pytest.fail(\"deliberately failing for demo purposes\")\n"
"E           Failed: deliberately failing for demo purposes\n"
"\n"
"test_backends.py:6: Failed\n"
"1 failed, 1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:289
msgid ""
"The first invocation with ``db == \"DB1\"`` passed while the second with "
"``db == \"DB2\"`` failed.  Our ``db`` fixture function has instantiated each "
"of the DB values during the setup phase while the ``pytest_generate_tests`` "
"generated two according calls to the ``test_db_initialized`` during the "
"collection phase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:294
msgid "Apply indirect on particular arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:296
msgid ""
"Very often parametrization uses more than one argument name. There is "
"opportunity to apply ``indirect`` parameter on particular arguments. It can "
"be done by passing list or tuple of arguments' names to ``indirect``. In the "
"example below there is a function ``test_indirect`` which uses two fixtures: "
"``x`` and ``y``. Here we give to indirect the list, which contains the name "
"of the fixture ``x``. The indirect parameter will be applied to this "
"argument only, and the value ``a`` will be passed to respective fixture "
"function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:303
msgid ""
"# content of test_indirect_list.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope='function')\n"
"def x(request):\n"
"    return request.param * 3\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope='function')\n"
"def y(request):\n"
"    return request.param * 2\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize('x, y', [('a', 'b')], indirect=['x'])\n"
"def test_indirect(x,y):\n"
"    assert x == 'aaa'\n"
"    assert y == 'b'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:319
msgid "The result of this test will be successful::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:321
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_indirect_list.py --collect-only\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"<Module 'test_indirect_list.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_indirect[a-b]'>\n"
"\n"
"======= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:334
msgid "Parametrizing test methods through per-class configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:339
msgid ""
"Here is an example ``pytest_generate_function`` function implementing a "
"parametrization scheme similar to Michael Foord's `unittest parametrizer`_ "
"but in a lot less code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:343
msgid ""
"# content of ./test_parametrize.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    # called once per each test function\n"
"    funcarglist = metafunc.cls.params[metafunc.function.__name__]\n"
"    argnames = list(funcarglist[0])\n"
"    metafunc.parametrize(argnames, [[funcargs[name] for name in argnames]\n"
"            for funcargs in funcarglist])\n"
"\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    # a map specifying multiple argument sets for a test method\n"
"    params = {\n"
"        'test_equals': [dict(a=1, b=2), dict(a=3, b=3), ],\n"
"        'test_zerodivision': [dict(a=1, b=0), ],\n"
"    }\n"
"\n"
"    def test_equals(self, a, b):\n"
"        assert a == b\n"
"\n"
"    def test_zerodivision(self, a, b):\n"
"        pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError, \"a/b\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:366
msgid ""
"Our test generator looks up a class-level definition which specifies which "
"argument sets to use for each test function.  Let's run it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:369
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q\n"
"F..\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ TestClass.test_equals[1-2] ________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_parametrize.TestClass object at 0xdeadbeef>, a = 1, b = 2\n"
"\n"
"    def test_equals(self, a, b):\n"
">       assert a == b\n"
"E       assert 1 == 2\n"
"\n"
"test_parametrize.py:18: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed, 2 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:384
msgid "Indirect parametrization with multiple fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:386
msgid ""
"Here is a stripped down real-life example of using parametrized testing for "
"testing serialization of objects between different python interpreters.  We "
"define a ``test_basic_objects`` function which is to be run with different "
"sets of arguments for its three arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:391
msgid ""
"``python1``: first python interpreter, run to pickle-dump an object to a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:392
msgid ""
"``python2``: second interpreter, run to pickle-load an object from a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:393
msgid "``obj``: object to be dumped/loaded"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:395
msgid ""
"\"\"\"\n"
"module containing a parametrized tests testing cross-python\n"
"serialization via the pickle module.\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"import py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import _pytest._code\n"
"\n"
"pythonlist = ['python2.6', 'python2.7', 'python3.3']\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=pythonlist)\n"
"def python1(request, tmpdir):\n"
"    picklefile = tmpdir.join(\"data.pickle\")\n"
"    return Python(request.param, picklefile)\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=pythonlist)\n"
"def python2(request, python1):\n"
"    return Python(request.param, python1.picklefile)\n"
"\n"
"class Python:\n"
"    def __init__(self, version, picklefile):\n"
"        self.pythonpath = py.path.local.sysfind(version)\n"
"        if not self.pythonpath:\n"
"            pytest.skip(\"%r not found\" %(version,))\n"
"        self.picklefile = picklefile\n"
"    def dumps(self, obj):\n"
"        dumpfile = self.picklefile.dirpath(\"dump.py\")\n"
"        dumpfile.write(_pytest._code.Source(\"\"\"\n"
"            import pickle\n"
"            f = open(%r, 'wb')\n"
"            s = pickle.dump(%r, f, protocol=2)\n"
"            f.close()\n"
"        \"\"\" % (str(self.picklefile), obj)))\n"
"        py.process.cmdexec(\"%s %s\" %(self.pythonpath, dumpfile))\n"
"\n"
"    def load_and_is_true(self, expression):\n"
"        loadfile = self.picklefile.dirpath(\"load.py\")\n"
"        loadfile.write(_pytest._code.Source(\"\"\"\n"
"            import pickle\n"
"            f = open(%r, 'rb')\n"
"            obj = pickle.load(f)\n"
"            f.close()\n"
"            res = eval(%r)\n"
"            if not res:\n"
"                raise SystemExit(1)\n"
"        \"\"\" % (str(self.picklefile), expression)))\n"
"        print (loadfile)\n"
"        py.process.cmdexec(\"%s %s\" %(self.pythonpath, loadfile))\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"obj\", [42, {}, {1:3},])\n"
"def test_basic_objects(python1, python2, obj):\n"
"    python1.dumps(obj)\n"
"    python2.load_and_is_true(\"obj == %s\" % obj)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:397
msgid ""
"Running it results in some skips if we don't have all the python "
"interpreters installed and otherwise runs all combinations (5 interpreters "
"times 5 interpreters times 3 objects to serialize/deserialize)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:399
msgid ""
". $ py.test -rs -q multipython.py\n"
"...........................\n"
"27 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:404
msgid "Indirect parametrization of optional implementations/imports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:406
msgid ""
"If you want to compare the outcomes of several implementations of a given "
"API, you can write test functions that receive the already imported "
"implementations and get skipped in case the implementation is not importable/"
"available.  Let's say we have a \"base\" implementation and the other "
"(possibly optimized ones) need to provide similar results::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:412
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def basemod(request):\n"
"    return pytest.importorskip(\"base\")\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\", params=[\"opt1\", \"opt2\"])\n"
"def optmod(request):\n"
"    return pytest.importorskip(request.param)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:424
msgid "And then a base implementation of a simple function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:426
msgid ""
"# content of base.py\n"
"def func1():\n"
"    return 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:430
msgid "And an optimized version::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:432
msgid ""
"# content of opt1.py\n"
"def func1():\n"
"    return 1.0001"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:436
msgid "And finally a little test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:438
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_func1(basemod, optmod):\n"
